@startuml
title ECommerce Backend - Docker Deployment Diagram

skinparam shadowing false

actor "Developer / API Consumer" as User

node "Docker Host" as Host {
  node "ecommerce-app\nASP.NET Core container" as App {
    artifact "ECommerceApp\nnet10.0 Web API" as ApiArtifact
    artifact ".env injected configuration" as Env
  }

  database "ecommerce-sqlserver\nSQL Server 2022" as SQL
  database "ecommerce-redis\nRedis 7.2" as Redis
  database "ecommerce-elasticsearch\nElasticsearch 8.9" as ES
  node "ecommerce-kibana\nKibana 8.9" as Kibana

  folder "sqlserver-data volume" as SqlVolume
  folder "redis-data volume" as RedisVolume
  folder "esdata volume" as EsVolume
}

cloud "SMTP Server" as SMTP

User --> App : HTTP/HTTPS\nAPP_PORT -> 8080
App --> SQL : EF Core\nConnectionStrings__EFCoreDBConnection
App --> Redis : catalog cache\nConnectionStrings__Redis
App --> ES : Serilog sink\nSERILOG_ELASTIC_URI
App --> SMTP : SMTP with SSL\nEmailSettings
Kibana --> ES : ELASTICSEARCH_HOSTS

SQL -- SqlVolume : /var/opt/mssql
Redis -- RedisVolume : /data
ES -- EsVolume : /usr/share/elasticsearch/data

note right of App
  docker-compose waits for SQL Server, Redis,
  and Elasticsearch health checks before starting the API.
end note

note bottom of App
  Runtime configuration includes JWT issuer/audience/key,
  admin emails, SMTP credentials, Redis, cache TTLs,
  and Serilog index settings.
end note

@enduml
